Issues Identified
I1 — Wrong canonical reference
The template (and CLAUDE.md) points to workspace/plan/active/COMPONENT-GOVERNANCE/component-framework-canonical.md. The ACTUAL canonical is docs-guide/frameworks/component-governance.mdx (689 lines, published, 12 sections). The workspace doc is working notes. Every pointer to the workspace path is wrong.

I2 — @type tag collision with official JSDoc
@type wrappers conflicts directly with the official JSDoc @type {string} (type annotation) tag. Any JSDoc tooling (IDE hover, TypeDoc, JSDoc generators) will misread our @type wrappers as a type declaration. Migration required: @type → @category.

I3 — @subniche is non-standard
@subniche is invented. The closest standard is @subcategory (used by TypeDoc). Migration: @subniche → @subcategory.

I4 — @example incorrectly marked forbidden
15/48 files (31%) already have @example. The governance standard marked it "forbidden" — but it IS an official JSDoc core tag and IS already in widespread use in the repo. The governance decision was wrong. It needs to be restored as required.

I5 — @accepts may be redundant
127 @accepts declarations across 48 files. The values (children, style, className, ...rest) are already covered by @param. @accepts is a machine-readable extensibility shorthand — useful for the registry generator and AI tooling — but its value needs to be explicitly justified or it should be absorbed into @param. The question: is the tooling reading it? If the registry generator uses it, keep it documented as an intentional non-standard tag. If nothing reads it, remove it.

I6 — No @requires pattern for composition dependencies
2 components have actual runtime imports of other Livepeer components (Lists.jsx → GotoLink; VideoData.jsx → YouTubeVideo). 16 components (33%) receive ReactNode/component props from the MDX page — and MDX authors have no guidance on what they need to import. @requires (official JSDoc tag) should document the runtime imports. A clear prop documentation pattern should tell MDX authors what they need to import.

I7 — Inter-component import governance conflict
docs-guide/frameworks/component-governance.mdx says components "must NOT import other .jsx component files." Lists.jsx and VideoData.jsx violate this. Either the rule is wrong and should be updated, or those two files need to be fixed. This needs a decision before the realignment.

I8 — Examples infrastructure missing
Governance doc says examples should exist in {category}/examples/{file}-examples.mdx. These don't exist (or are sparse). 33 additional component files have no @example tag at all.

I9 — @deprecated has no replacement pattern
3 components are marked @status deprecated with no @see pointing to the replacement. Authors have no guidance.

Realignment Plan
Phase 1 — Tag standard realignment (touches every file + all tooling)
1a. Migrate @type → @category

Before	After
@type wrappers	@category wrappers
@type elements	@category elements
Scope: 127 declarations across 48 files + registry generator + pre-commit validator + component-governance.mdx.

1b. Migrate @subniche → @subcategory

Before	After
@subniche tables	@subcategory tables
Same scope as 1a.

1c. Restore @example as required

Move @example from "forbidden" to "required" in governance docs
Minimum format: one JSX usage example showing import + basic use
15 files already have it; 33 need it added
Format to standardise on:


@example
// Basic usage:
import { ComponentName } from "/snippets/components/category/subniche/File.jsx";
<ComponentName prop="value" />
1d. Decision on @accepts

Two options:

Keep: Annotate it explicitly as a non-standard tooling tag; update governance docs to say "intentionally non-standard — read by registry generator for AI companion manifest." Keep alongside @param.
Remove: Absorb extensibility declaration into @param entries for style, className, and ...rest. Simpler, purer JSDoc alignment. Requires updating registry generator.
Recommendation: Keep, but label it explicitly as a custom tooling tag in governance docs, not a JSDoc tag. The @accepts values drive the AI companion manifest — removing it would need a registry generator rewrite.

1e. Add @requires for runtime imports

Only 2 files currently have actual imports. Add:


@requires snippets/components/elements/links/Links.jsx
to Lists.jsx and VideoData.jsx.

For composition slots (ReactNode props) — document in @example with the import shown. The MDX author can see what to import by reading the example. Do NOT add @requires for "what the consumer imports" — that's a misuse of the tag. The example is the right place.

1f. Decide the import governance conflict

Option A: Allow inter-component imports (update the "must NOT import" rule) — aligns with actual practice.
Option B: Fix Lists.jsx and VideoData.jsx to not import — pass the sub-component as a prop instead.

This is a human decision (architectural). The plan proceeds after this is resolved.

Phase 2 — Examples infrastructure
2a. @example in JSDoc (all 48 files)

Add at least one @example block to every component that's missing it (33 files). Generated or hand-written per component.

2b. Auto-generated examples pages

Structure:


snippets/components/
  elements/
    examples/
      elements-examples.mdx   ← auto-generated
  wrappers/
    examples/
      wrappers-examples.mdx   ← auto-generated
  displays/
    examples/
      displays-examples.mdx
  scaffolding/
    examples/
      scaffolding-examples.mdx
  integrators/
    examples/
      integrators-examples.mdx
Generator reads @example from each component's JSDoc and compiles per-category MDX pages. Pages show: component name, description, example code, import line.

Alternatives considered:

Per-subniche pages (e.g., wrappers/tables/examples.mdx) — more granular but 30+ files
Per-component pages — too many files, hard to browse
Recommendation: per-category (6 pages), with anchor links per component
Phase 3 — Governance docs housekeeping
3a. Update all canonical references

Every file pointing to workspace/plan/active/COMPONENT-GOVERNANCE/component-framework-canonical.md must point to docs-guide/frameworks/component-governance.mdx. This includes: CLAUDE.md, template file, AGENTS.md, component-registry generator, pre-commit hook.

The workspace doc becomes a working draft only — not canonical.

3b. Update governance doc for new tag names

docs-guide/frameworks/component-governance.mdx (689 lines) needs:

@type → @category throughout
@subniche → @subcategory throughout
@example restored as required
@requires added as a new tag
@accepts: annotated as custom tooling tag (not JSDoc)
3c. Add @deprecated replacement pattern

Add to governance docs:


@status      deprecated
@see         ReplacementComponentName
Update the 3 deprecated components to include @see.

Phase 4 — Tooling updates
The following scripts need updating for the tag name changes:

Script	Change
generate-component-registry.js	Read @category and @subcategory instead of @type and @subniche
check-component-jsdoc-placement.js (planned)	Validate @category and @subcategory
check-component-health.js	Check for @example presence (new requirement)
generate-ui-templates.js	Update snippet generation to use new tag names
component-registry.json field names	Rename category → stays category; subniche → subcategory
.vscode/components.code-snippets	Regenerate from updated registry
Build order
Human decision first: resolve I6 (import governance conflict) and I5 (@accepts keep/remove)
Phase 1a + 1b: migrate tag names — one pass, all 48 files + tooling update
Phase 1c: @example enforcement — add to 33 missing files
Phase 1d/e/f: @requires, @deprecated, @accepts finalization
Phase 3: governance docs update (canonical reference + content changes)
Phase 2: examples infrastructure — build generator, run for 6 categories
Phase 4: tooling updates (registry generator, validators, snippets)
What this does NOT touch
Component FUNCTIONALITY — no JSX changes
Folder structure — taxonomy is correct, only tag names change
docs.json navigation
@aiDiscoverability and @dataSource — these are justified custom tags, keep as-is
@component — keep as-is (useful identity declaration, not in JSDoc standard but not conflicting)
